<figure class="viz" aria-labelledby="toolchain-title">
  <figcaption id="toolchain-title">
    Frontier interpretability works at four different levels
  </figcaption>

  <div class="levels">
    <section>
      <span>Features</span>
      <strong>Sparse autoencoders</strong>
      <p>Decompose activations into reusable directions.</p>
      <small>Question: what is represented?</small>
    </section>
    <section>
      <span>Circuits</span>
      <strong>Transcoders and attribution graphs</strong>
      <p>Trace how features contribute to a chosen output.</p>
      <small>Question: how is the output computed?</small>
    </section>
    <section>
      <span>Reports</span>
      <strong>Natural-language autoencoders</strong>
      <p>Translate an activation through a text bottleneck.</p>
      <small>Question: what can a reader inspect quickly?</small>
    </section>
    <section>
      <span>Workspace</span>
      <strong>Jacobian lens</strong>
      <p>Read and edit concepts poised to affect future outputs.</p>
      <small>Question: what is available for flexible reasoning?</small>
    </section>
  </div>

  <div class="rule">
    A label becomes stronger evidence when a causal intervention changes the predicted behavior.
  </div>
</figure>

